{
  "texts": [
    "Theorem 4.3 yields the existence of a unique metric g B ∈ c such that (20b) holds, and hence (g B, ρ, h) ∈ HE.",
    "If we had a different representative C φ • ρ ∈ Hom red (π 1 (B), G), φ ∈ G, then the corresponding triple would clearly be (gB, C φ • ρ, φ • h) ∼ (g B, ρ, h).",
    "On the other hand, given f ∈ Aut(B 2, c), then f * [(P, Φ)] corresponds to ρ • f * ∈ Hom red (π 1 (B), G).",
    "The triple associated to ρ • f * is clearly ( f * g B, ρ • f *, h • f), which is also equivalent to (g B, ρ, h).Conversely, if (g B, ρ, h) ∈ HE, then Theorem 4.2 implies ρ ∈ Hom(π 1 (B), G) is reductive, so the nonabelian Hodge correspondence gives [(P, Φ)] ∈ M(B, G).",
    "Since h is weakly conformal by (20b), Lemma 4.9 yields tr Φ 2 = 0, so[(P, Φ)] ∈ N. Finally, if (g ′ B, ρ ′, h ′) = ( f * g B, C φ • ρ • f *, φ • h • f) ∼ (g B, ρ, h), then ρ ′ = C φ • ρ • f *defines the same conjugacy class as ρ (up to pull-back), so (g ′ B, ρ ′, h ′) defines the same equivalence class f * [(P, Φ)] ∈ N as (g B, ρ, h)."
  ]
}